{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"78a36cb0-f2d9-401d-aa29-2441d0541099","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** (most likely):\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<machine>.ips`. Recent crashes appear here within seconds.\n\n2. **Console.app** — open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar.\n\n3. **Core dumps** (if enabled):\n   ```bash\n   # Check/enable core dumps\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   # Cores go to /cores/core.<pid>\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n   Core dumps are disabled by default on macOS and require SIP adjustments on newer versions.\n\n**Tip:** The `.ips` crash report in `DiagnosticReports` is usually the easiest to find and contains the stack trace, signal info, and thread state — no extra setup required.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b4f6b66a-ffc2-4da4-a404-9db7821bb10f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":283,"requestId":"C3D3:27C37:1D9981B:212FACB:6A07C20E"},"id":"f1f577eb-6a4b-4732-847a-dad586b4d898","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:02:15.883Z","parentId":"0ba4ec58-b5fb-4a9b-ab9d-c93d1bd4520f"}
